<p>Revenue =Rs.29,111 Cr</p>
<p>Export Revenue = Rs.12,216 Cr</p>
<p>So Domestic revenue must be â€“</p>
<p>29111 â€“ 12216</p>
<p>= <strong>Rs.16,895 Crs.</strong></p>
<p>Once we have the revenue split from domestic and exports, we can do few other things to set up the revenue model.</p>
<h2><strong>6.3 â€“ Connecting the dots </strong></h2>
<p>We have now gathered all the info required to build the revenue model. We now have to plug these values into an excel sheet and give it a logical sequence. Please note that if you are doing this yourself, as a first step, you will have to get the historical data from the annual report.&nbsp; In the section above, Iâ€™ve highlighted how the data is collected. Hopefully, that will help you accelerate your data collection process.</p>
<p>Given the data in hand, here are the steps that Iâ€™ll follow to develop the revenue model. As I have stressed earlier, the steps that I follow make sense to me; if you feel there is a better way, you should explore. Remember, there is no prescribed methods to build a model.</p>
<p>But I hope these steps will give you a good starting point.</p>
<p>Here is the overview of the steps Iâ€™ll carry out on excel â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>Organize the capacity data</li>
<li>Gather the International sales data, i.e. the number of units of bikes and CV sold</li>
<li>Gather the India sales data, i.e. the number of units of bikes and CV sold</li>
<li>Add up the sales data to get consolidated bikes and CV sales data</li>
<li>Input the historical revenue data</li>
<li>Calculate the average cost of sale of bike and CV</li>
<li>Identify the trend in change of average cost of sale</li>
<li>Project the average price of the vehicle and reverse engineer the revenue data from the average prices.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>If the steps above confuse you, then donâ€™t worry, we will execute each of the steps, one at a time.</p>
<p>As a first step, we set up our excel sheet with the indexation. Iâ€™ve discussed this in the earlier chapters, so Iâ€™ll directly post the snapshot for your reference.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10085" height="126" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 525px) 100vw, 525px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup-300x72.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup-300x72.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup-1024x244.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup-768x183.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-9_setup.png 1228w" width="525"/></a></p>
<p>I guess you are reasonably familiar with the layout. Columns A and B are indexed, C expanded, panes frozen at E3. The actual financial years stated from F1 to J1, and the estimated years from K1 to O1.</p>
<p>I have organized the manufacturing capacity data. Note I have segregated this in terms of bikes and CV, but you can also arrange the data from the manufacturing plant perspective.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10086" height="141" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 528px) 100vw, 528px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity-300x80.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity-300x80.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity-1024x273.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity-768x205.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-10_capacity.png 1193w" width="528"/></a></p>
<p>I have populated the manufacturing capacity numbers â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10087" height="123" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 528px) 100vw, 528px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers-300x70.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers-300x70.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers-1024x239.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers-768x179.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-11_capacitynumbers.png 1361w" width="528"/></a></p>
<p>Note, the numbers are constant historically and for the future years as well.</p>
<p>Next up is the sales data. As I mentioned earlier, Iâ€™m interested in identifying the bike and CV sales in India and Internationally. Once I have the data, Iâ€™m also interested in year on year (YoY) changes in sales data.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10088" height="249" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 530px) 100vw, 530px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data-300x141.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data-300x141.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data-1024x483.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data-768x362.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-12_sales-data.png 1376w" width="530"/></a></p>
<p>As we saw earlier, most of the sales data is available in the annual report, except for the India sales data for bikes. But this is ok; the company gives us the total bike sales (India + International) and the total international bike sales data.</p>
<p>If we calculate the difference, we get the India bikes sales data. So a bit of number jugglery that you will have to do.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10089" height="267" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 530px) 100vw, 530px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes-300x151.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes-300x151.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes-1024x515.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes-768x386.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-13_total-bikes.png 1362w" width="530"/></a></p>
<p>Next, we calculate the YoY change (in percentage) bikes and CV sales in the Indian and the International markets.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10090" height="269" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 531px) 100vw, 531px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy-300x152.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy-300x152.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy-1024x519.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy-768x389.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-14_yoy.png 1362w" width="531"/></a></p>
<p>The math is simple for the YoY change â€“</p>
<p>= this yearâ€™s sales data/ previous yearâ€™s sales data â€“ 1</p>
<p>= year on year change in sales, expressed in percentage.</p>
<p>The idea of calculating the YoY percentage change is to identify consistent trends if any. But clearly, there is no trend in the data we have.</p>
<p>We could have taken a rolling average of the yoy change and projected for future years if there was a trend. But now, we have to assume a flat YoY change.</p>
<p>Iâ€™ll project the YoY change without thinking much (to move ahead quickly), but of course, if this were a serious model (based on which youâ€™d invest), then we would have to spend some time before we make the YoY change assumptions.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10079" height="281" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 533px) 100vw, 533px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass-300x158.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass-300x158.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass-1024x540.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass-768x405.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-15_yoyass.png 1371w" width="533"/></a></p>
<p>You can see the assumption Iâ€™ve made for the sales YoY change in percentage. You can also see the calculation that Iâ€™ve made to project the future yearâ€™s sale of bikes and CV. Iâ€™ve completed the math, and here is how the excel sheet looks â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10091" height="277" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 535px) 100vw, 535px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total-300x155.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total-300x155.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total-1024x530.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total-768x397.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-16_total.png 1368w" width="535"/></a></p>
<p>Please note, Iâ€™ve summed up the bike and CV sales from both the Indian and the International markets to get the total sales. For your reference, Iâ€™ve highlighted the total sales of bikes for FY22E.</p>
<p>In the next step, we move our attention to the revenue data. Iâ€™ve taken the revenue data (India and International) from the annual report.</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10092" height="188" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 537px) 100vw, 537px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev-300x105.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev-300x105.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev-1024x358.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev-768x269.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-17_rev.png 1364w" width="537"/></a></p>
<p>Below the revenue numbers, Iâ€™ve set up excel to calculate the average sale cost for vehicles (bikes + CV) across the Indian and the international markets. To calculate this, we need to divide the India revenue number by the India vehicles sold data.</p>
<p>Let me do this math for FY 17 â€“</p>
<p>Revenue from India (FY17) = Rs.14,815 Cr</p>
<p>Total vehicles sold in India (bikes+ CV) = 22,54,617</p>
<p>Average selling price of a vehicle = 14815*(10^7)/2254617</p>
<p>= Rs.65,709.61/-</p>
<p>If you wonder why I used 10^7 in the math above, then it is to get the revenue number in Crores.</p>
<p>Here is how it looks on Excel â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10094" height="268" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 528px) 100vw, 528px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost-300x152.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost-300x152.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost-1024x518.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost-768x388.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-18_avgcost.png 1371w" width="528"/></a></p>
<p>Iâ€™ve calculated the YoY change in average cost of sale as well. I hope at this stage; you can figure what to do next. If you do, then Iâ€™d be happy to know that my notes are helping you think ahead ðŸ˜Š</p>
<p>Anyway, here are the last two steps to complete the revenue model.</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>Assume a YoY change for future years, it could be a rolling average, or it could be a flat assumption</li>
<li>Project the average cost of sale in the Indian and the International market</li>
<li>Multiply the avg cost of sale and the number of vehicles sold to get the revenue in the Indian and International market</li>
<li>Sum up both to get the total revenue.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Iâ€™ve executed all the above steps in excel, and here is how it looks â€“</p>
<p><a href="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final.png"><img alt="" class="aligncenter wp-image-10095" height="266" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 529px) 100vw, 529px" src="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final-300x151.png" srcset="https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final-300x151.png 300w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final-1024x517.png 1024w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final-768x388.png 768w, https://zerodha.com/varsity/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Image-19_final.png 1403w" width="529"/></a></p>
<p>I have highlighted both the cells so that you can see the formula Iâ€™ve used.</p>
<p>Here are few other things that you can do with the revenue model â€“</p>
<ul>
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul>
<li>We have the total bike and CV sales data. Compare this with the production data. Ensure the company is not selling more than what it is making. If yes, then our model may be wrong and needs some tweaking</li>
<li>If the vehicles sold are close to manufactured, the company may have to invest in a CAPEX cycle. This is valuable information from an overall financial modelling perspective</li>
<li>Calculate the capacity utilization, i.e. number of vehicles manufacture versus the number of vehicles sold.</li>
<li>Calculate the market share. You can get the industry bike/CV sales data from an industry report (guess even the annual report contains this), contrast this with what the company has sold, and get the market share number.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>I guess this has turned into a lengthy chapter; Iâ€™ll stop it at this. But I hope this chapter has given you a sense of how you can develop a companyâ€™s revenue model using a common-sense approach. Always remember to start your revenue model by asking few basic questions.</p>
<p>The revenue model we have built here can be used for other auto manufacturing companies like Hero Motors, TVS, MRF, Maruti, Tata Motors, and even Tesla!</p>
